│       is stdlib; orjson is actively used in the code for both serialization and fingerprinting.
├── Binary object serialization
│   ├── Candidates : pickle, orjson
│   ├── Used APIs  : pickle.dumps, orjson.dumps, orjson.loads
│   ├── Pitfalls   : pickle can serialize arbitrary Python objects including custom classes; orjson is limited to JSON-compatible types; pickle output is not 
│   │   human-readable or cross-language; orjson output is JSON bytes readable by any language; pickle has well-known arbitrary code execution risk on deserialization of
│   │   untrusted data — orjson is safe in this regard; orjson always returns bytes; pickle.dumps also returns bytes, so the interface is compatible for dict payloads; 
│   │   Switching serialize_pickle to orjson would break for non-JSON-serializable objects (e.g. custom class instances, sets, tuples become arrays)
│   ├── Constraints: requires_connector
